args: Yes, thank you. These should make for a\nlovely table setting.
How sweet of you, Nino. Thank— *gasp*
You have to burn those! NOW! Otherwise—
It seems my warning came too late.
When plucked, that flower seems to emit\na scent that lures in fiends.
We can't detect it, but apparently it's, like,\nthe fiend equivalent of catnip. Or a jumbo\nplatter of fresh chocolate chip cookies!
I'm so sorry. I had no idea.
It's our fault for not explaining earlier.\nBut for now, we have more pressing\nmatters...
There's a village ahead.\nWe have to stop them here!
(With their numbers, we'll be wiped\nout unless I fight at full strength.)
(But they'll see my wing.\nI'll have to explain who I really am.)
(I've put both a new friend and an entire\nvillage in danger.)
(This is no time for selfish doubts.\nAncestor, lend me your power!)
Cleo, back me up as best you can!
I can fight! I won't let a single one of\nthem past!
That seems to be the last of them.
Yeah! I burned all of the flowers,\nso we should be all right. So, uh...
Nino. That was a faerie wing, wasn't it?\nBut why just one? What's the story there?
Are you a faerie? Or... What are you?
(As soon as I tell them, our friendship is\nover. What's worse, it will mean putting\nall of them in danger.)
(I would rather part ways without saying a\nword than do them harm.)
It was a pleasure staying with you all.\n...Goodbye.
Wha?! Hey, wait! Nino!\nWhere are you going?!
(It's well and truly dark out, but\nI can't go back to the castle now.)
(May as well find a clearing to bed down\nfor the night.)
You... You were the one back at the village\nwho Elisanne laid flat!
What, turned to banditry out here with your\nlittle friends now that you can't fleece the\nvillagers out of their money? I pity you.
Ugh, you a friend of that she-devil?! I'm\nstill aching from the lumps she gave me.
But I can find it in my heart to forgive,\nif you leave all your belongings behind.\nNow, let's have 'em!
Ain't it obvious, girl? We take 'em by force!
What kinda monster is she?! \nA wing just sprouted from her back!
Heh heh. We've struck gold, boys!
I see my previous lesson didn't stick.\nBack to your mischief already?
It's just one more girl, lads! Get 'em both!
Gladly. This won't end the way it did the\nlast time, wench!
Nino, can you stand? We need to\nget through this. We can talk after.
...Well? You're not going to ask, Elisanne?
Hah... That might be the easier way,\nat this point.
I wanted to keep it hidden, but I don't\nsuppose I have that option anymore.
I caused you all such trouble, and then\nI just ran away. You even saw my wing.\nWhat can I even do to make ame—
Your wing. The way it catches\nthe moonlight. It's beautiful.
It's a faerie wing. And I'm a human.\nYou don't think I'm a freak of nature?
Why would I? You have a wing, and\nthat is that. It's not my place to pry.
This afternoon, you revealed your secret so\nthat you could fight to protect my friends\nand the people of this land.
You clearly wished to keep it hidden, yet\nyou put the safety of others before your\nown desires.
That alone is enough to earn you my trust.\nNo matter who or what you might be, I\nbelieve you. I believe IN you.
And I'm certain everyone else at the\nHalidom would say the same. At this\npoint, you're our friend, Nino. One of us.
Of course. Why else would I come looking\nfor you? Shall we? The others are waiting.
*SOB* NINOOOOO! I'm so glad you're back!\nI was really freaking out thinking how you\nwere out there wandering in the dark!
I'm glad to see you're all right. I have a\nhot bowl of soup waiting for you. Go and\nwarm yourself up.
Er, thank you... Both of you.
(They really aren't asking. They\nlegitimately intend to accept me here.)
(And honestly? I believe they would.\nNo matter who I turned out to be.)
I'm sorry to have worried you.\nI... I'm back now. To stay.
Good. Welcome home to the Halidom,\nNino.
